summary:
6. Stresses the need to accelerate work on the draft protocol on the return of refugees and measures for economic rehabilitation;

7. Calls upon the parties, in particular the Abkhaz side, to engage in negotiations on core political questions;

8. Welcomes documents signed at the Yalta meeting on confidence-building measures and urges their implementation;

9. Calls upon the parties to resume work in the Coordinating Council;

10. Urges the parties to work together to clarify recent incidents, release hostages, and bring perpetrators to justice;

11. Reaffirms the unacceptability of demographic changes and the inalienable right of refugees and internally displaced persons to return to their homes;

12. Urges the parties to address urgently the status of spontaneous returnees to the Gali district.
Here is a summarized version of the Security Council document:

The Security Council:

* Welcomes measures to improve the situation of refugees and internally displaced persons, and their right to return home in secure and dignified conditions (para 13).
* Notes the joint assessment mission to the Gali district and looks forward to discussion on implementing its recommendations (para 14).
* Deplores violations of the Moscow Agreement, particularly military exercises conducted in June and July 2001 (para 15).
* Expresses concern at restrictions on UNOMIG's freedom of movement and urges both sides to comply with the Moscow Agreement (para 16).
* Recalls that both parties are responsible for the security of UNOMIG and other international personnel (para 17).
* Urges the Georgian side to stop activities of illegal armed groups crossing into Abkhazia (para 18).
* Welcomes UNOMIG's review of its security arrangements (para 19).
* Extends UNOMIG's mandate until 31 January 2002, subject to review (para 20).
* Requests the Secretary-General to keep the Council informed and report on the situation and progress of the political settlement (para 21).
* Decides to remain actively seized of the matter (para 22).
